    {
      "id": "aelUn_vNfwT3eIor9fYbr",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1623.9386827615265,
      "y": 8834.671679786377,
      "width": 1623.167724609375,
      "height": 1215,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#e03131",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b22",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 254717407,
      "version": 1614,
      "versionNonce": 462822669,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1767869369584,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "if we are working on a very small\nscale this evaluator machine and app server can be running \non the same machine we can have same EC2 instance running\nour python code and evaluator logic but for now asume\nwe have good budget and we have diff evaluator machine this \nis some diff EC2 instance\n\n\n\nThe problem is even if the App server send the request to evaluator machine\nwe can't run the code directly on the evaluator machine\n\nWhy -> if someboday sends a fork bomb like recursion that never ends our\n   evaluator machine will go down\n\nSO what is the solution -> Solution comes with Docker or some kind of a \nVirtualmachine So in our Evaluator machine we are going to create small virtualmachine\nour code is going to run inside this virtualmachine and not directly on the actual\nmachine , if somebody send a fork bomb this VM will go down not the actual evaluator\nmachine. we can easily put VM using Docker Containers. Inside this Docker Container\nwe will run our code and do the remaining evaluation So our code will run on docker \ncontainer.\n\nInside our Evaluator machine there will be multiple VM evaluting mulitple submission at\nsame point of time\nand we will scale our Evaluator machines as well we will have many Evaluator machines as well\nHorizontally scaled",
      "fontSize": 36,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "if we are working on a very small\nscale this evaluator machine and app server can be running \non the same machine we can have same EC2 instance running\nour python code and evaluator logic but for now asume\nwe have good budget and we have diff evaluator machine this \nis some diff EC2 instance\n\n\n\nThe problem is even if the App server send the request to evaluator machine\nwe can't run the code directly on the evaluator machine\n\nWhy -> if someboday sends a fork bomb like recursion that never ends our\n   evaluator machine will go down\n\nSO what is the solution -> Solution comes with Docker or some kind of a \nVirtualmachine So in our Evaluator machine we are going to create small virtualmachine\nour code is going to run inside this virtualmachine and not directly on the actual\nmachine , if somebody send a fork bomb this VM will go down not the actual evaluator\nmachine. we can easily put VM using Docker Containers. Inside this Docker Container\nwe will run our code and do the remaining evaluation So our code will run on docker \ncontainer.\n\nInside our Evaluator machine there will be multiple VM evaluting mulitple submission at\nsame point of time\nand we will scale our Evaluator machines as well we will have many Evaluator machines as well\nHorizontally scaled",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
