    {
      "id": "lkGsXoxcK_DSV_TGLSDnb",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 257.0282721165404,
      "y": -10779.85234740064,
      "width": 2731.2470703125,
      "height": 1575,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "#b2f2bb",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b7R",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1509245360,
      "version": 3341,
      "versionNonce": 1624128086,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1768050349314,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Submission service & Evaluator machines are different EC2 instances\n\nSubmission service just take the request and forward that couple of places and give response back so EC2 instance for this will be of lower grade\nbut evaluator service has to do lot of things \nCreate new docker container\nrun the code inside docker\nmatch all the test case\n\nso it will use most powerfull EC2 machine\n\nOnce Evaluator Service has some evaluation result how it will tell to Client -> Many solutions\n1. Polling -> Client will keep on polling to the evaluator service lets say evaluator service exposes some REST API using which client\n    can poll for the evaluation response llike I made a submission with id 33 what is the result No result ok after 2 minute again \n    I made a submission with id 33 what is the result No result ok and so on keep on polling\n\nbut pollling is not a good way why -> Our evaluator service will be bomborded unnecessarily like 100 time polling req comes 99 times\nno result hence there will be a load in evaluator service unnecessarily Hence we need something else better that this\n\n2. Once evaluator service will get result it will put that result into Queue, Submission service will keep on take that from evaluator queue and update entry\n    on DB and give the response to client\n3 Instead of Queue Structure we can use streaming structure like kafka\n    Lets say we have prepared submmission Queue using RabbitMQ in RabbitMQ there is a job payload if that payload is read by someone then that get \n    dequed from the queue but that is not the case with Kafka in kafka there is a pointer kind of structure just pointer moves not dequeud so Kafka\n    gives a great persistence as well so in this case we can revisit old submission as well we can see what submission is made at what time.\n    if evaluator service not given response for any submission then we can retry as well\n\nthere is two way by which we can send data to the client via submission service\n1. Client can poll submission service but again same issue will be there like client polls 100 times and 99 times there is no respoinse hence unnecessary load\n    on submission service\n2. Server side event(server sent data) -> in this server can directly send data back to the client, without client request hence our server will not \n    bombarded with unnessesary request so this we can use\n3. Websocket -> It is also a protocol that is based on top of TCP connection, websocket is kind of like a pipeline that we setup between two machines\nand these two machines can send and receive request from each other in real time\n\n",
      "fontSize": 36,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Submission service & Evaluator machines are different EC2 instances\n\nSubmission service just take the request and forward that couple of places and give response back so EC2 instance for this will be of lower grade\nbut evaluator service has to do lot of things \nCreate new docker container\nrun the code inside docker\nmatch all the test case\n\nso it will use most powerfull EC2 machine\n\nOnce Evaluator Service has some evaluation result how it will tell to Client -> Many solutions\n1. Polling -> Client will keep on polling to the evaluator service lets say evaluator service exposes some REST API using which client\n    can poll for the evaluation response llike I made a submission with id 33 what is the result No result ok after 2 minute again \n    I made a submission with id 33 what is the result No result ok and so on keep on polling\n\nbut pollling is not a good way why -> Our evaluator service will be bomborded unnecessarily like 100 time polling req comes 99 times\nno result hence there will be a load in evaluator service unnecessarily Hence we need something else better that this\n\n2. Once evaluator service will get result it will put that result into Queue, Submission service will keep on take that from evaluator queue and update entry\n    on DB and give the response to client\n3 Instead of Queue Structure we can use streaming structure like kafka\n    Lets say we have prepared submmission Queue using RabbitMQ in RabbitMQ there is a job payload if that payload is read by someone then that get \n    dequed from the queue but that is not the case with Kafka in kafka there is a pointer kind of structure just pointer moves not dequeud so Kafka\n    gives a great persistence as well so in this case we can revisit old submission as well we can see what submission is made at what time.\n    if evaluator service not given response for any submission then we can retry as well\n\nthere is two way by which we can send data to the client via submission service\n1. Client can poll submission service but again same issue will be there like client polls 100 times and 99 times there is no respoinse hence unnecessary load\n    on submission service\n2. Server side event(server sent data) -> in this server can directly send data back to the client, without client request hence our server will not \n    bombarded with unnessesary request so this we can use\n3. Websocket -> It is also a protocol that is based on top of TCP connection, websocket is kind of like a pipeline that we setup between two machines\nand these two machines can send and receive request from each other in real time\n\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
